 We're going to discuss in the beginning on how the fragmentation affecting the region and what is the business model in the European economy in the future.

61
00:09:51,000 --> 00:10:00,000
 I would like to ask you, please, to start. And for the first question, I would like to ask you, how do you think the economic and geopolitical fragmentation,

62
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:07,000
 reflecting both the IMF and the EU concerns impacting the region's growth prospects and business models,

63
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:14,000
 also regarding the fact that recent downgrade of the regional growth was put to 2.4% for 2025?

64
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:29,000
 So clearly the European Union has been a huge push for the countries of our region, the CESI countries, to convert rapidly to EU levels.

65
00:10:29,000 --> 00:10:36,000
 You know, every country that has become a member of the European Union has become a high-income economy.

66
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:43,000
 It's a massive improvement. Since 1990, 27 countries around the world have become high-income.

67
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:50,000
 13 of them are in the European Union. And the other are resource-rich, oil and gas-rich, or tourism-dependent islands.

68
00:10:50,000 --> 00:10:57,000
 So the EU obviously has been a huge impetus for development of both EU members and applicants,

69
00:10:57,000 --> 00:11:02,000
 or those that may not have even a chance to join the EU. Why?

70
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:09,000
 There's been an alignment of institutions, and even those that are not joining the EU are trying to replicate those institutions in the EU that work very well.

71
00:11:09,000 --> 00:11:17,000
 There's been a surge in trade. I mean, you know, in our region, Czech Republic, Czechia, sends 80% of its exports to the EU.

72
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:21,000
 Bulgaria sends 65%. On average, it's about 65%.

73
00:11:21,000 --> 00:11:25,000
 Huge, huge, huge role for trade, huge role for investment.

74
00:11:25,000 --> 00:11:32,000
 70% of FDI to the region is from the EU, whether it's through value chains or other means.

75
00:11:32,000 --> 00:11:38,000
 So, it's a massive push for the maturity and the convergence of the region.

76
00:11:38,000 --> 00:11:46,000
 And so, therefore, any fragmentation, whether it's global or within the EU, I think it has a massive impact, negative impact on our countries.

77
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:55,000
 I mean, somebody was mentioning earlier, you know, among the countries of the region, the highest share of exports to the US is 5% for Turkey.

78
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:00,000
 This is the lowest share of exports in East Asia for Australia.

79
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:07,000
 So, our countries are not directly exposed to the US, but they are massively exposed to secondary effects through the European Union.

80
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:17,000
 So, the way the EU is performing in the world and the way the EU is performing within itself is, I think, it's massive positive or negative impact.

81
00:12:17,000 --> 00:12:27,000
 And so, therefore, I think it matters tremendously in times of, in more difficult times as we have now, how do we address the internal fragmentation in the EU?

82
00:12:27,000 --> 00:12:35,000
 There are a lot of sources of inefficiencies, a lot of sources that could be addressed to deliver faster growth in productivity and in jobs and in output.

83
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:38,000
 And so, therefore, I think this is absolutely essential.

84
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:42,000
 Let's focus on that, because it benefits the EU, but benefits our countries as well.

85
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:58,000
 Deborah, based on the latest EIB investment survey, what are the main opportunities and the risks for these region countries as they are trying to, as well, adapt their business models and investment strategies?

86
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:08,000
 I very much think I follow the storyline, I think, that we all have in mind.

87
00:13:08,000 --> 00:13:13,000
 The fact that the region has massively benefited from EU integration.

88
00:13:13,000 --> 00:13:15,000
 And I think we should never forget it.

89
00:13:15,000 --> 00:13:18,000
 There is the income conversion part, the trade part.

90
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:27,000
 One data that we also were looking at is that if you look at since 2000, the export performance of some of the countries of the region,

91
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:30,000
 is really like Germany, like Korea.

92
00:13:30,000 --> 00:13:42,000
 So it's really a pick-up of this region that has become central in European value chains, but also extra EU trade is quite relevant.

93
00:13:42,000 --> 00:13:48,000
 And also, there is another element that I think is quite interesting.

94
00:13:48,000 --> 00:14:01,000
 In the financial market shocks that we have seen after the US trade tariff mess, Europe overall is more considered as a safe haven.

95
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:12,000
 And countries in the region, most of them have also benefited, also the non-euro countries, of being safer than the US, if you want.

96
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:21,000
 There were some countries more affected for local political uncertainty, but mostly the region has been benefiting.

97
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:24,000
 So I think we start from that point.

98
00:14:24,000 --> 00:14:30,000
 There is one point of which I was reflecting, related also to the panel.

99
00:14:30,000 --> 00:14:49,000
 And probably because most of these countries are small economies, they are today also experiencing, somehow more than other countries, the cost of the unfinished work in terms of integration at the European level.

100
00:14:49,000 --> 00:14:58,000
 And we have our survey that looks at European firms, we do it every year, we monitor different developments.

101
00:14:58,000 --> 00:15:01,000
 And there are a few data that I think are quite interesting.

102
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:10,000
 One, we ask the firms if they export to another EU country whether they face barriers in the market.

103
00:15:10,000 --> 00:15:16,000
 Now, overall in Europe, 60% say they face barriers.

104
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:21,000
 They shouldn't because in an integrated market, you should have no barriers in Europe.

105
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:25,000
 60% European level say there are barriers.

106
00:15:25,000 --> 00:15:27,000
 In Central Eastern Europe, it's 80%.

107
00:15:27,000 --> 00:15:39,000
 So I was thinking that's related probably to the unfinished market and by being a smaller economy, so they have more frictions and they face it more.

108
00:15:39,000 --> 00:15:44,000
 The other point is that there is also some internal work to be done.

109
00:15:44,000 --> 00:16:01,000
 We calculate what we call the cost of bureaucracy is coming from asking the firms how many people they are fully dedicated to dealing with bureaucracy.

110
00:16:01,000 --> 00:16:11,000
 It comes out that at the European level is some 1.5% of turnover of the companies at this cost of bureaucracy.

111
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:14,000
 In Central Eastern Europe, it's 2.5%.

112
00:16:14,000 --> 00:16:22,000
 So small numbers, but the energy bill for companies is some 4% of GDP.

113
00:16:22,000 --> 00:16:27,000
 So 2.5% is not so little and the region seems to have a little bit more.

114
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:37,000
 So there is also some internal work related to easing the business environment that the region should look at.

115
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:48,000
 And then another boundary, if you want, in terms of that the region may be experiencing is related to the financial side.

116
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:53,000
 If you want, the region is quite integrated on the banking side.

117
00:16:53,000 --> 00:17:02,000
 We all know that banks are quite ramificated in the region, international banks operating in the region.

118
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:06,000
 And they really have a rule in terms of integrating the market.

119
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:17,000
 But on the capital market side, the lack of a European integrated capital market and investment and saving union in the region is more perceived.

120
00:17:17,000 --> 00:17:24,000
 Because they don't have very strong markets and very big markets on their side.

121
00:17:24,000 --> 00:17:31,000
 So the lack of the integration at the European level translates even stronger in the region.

122
00:17:31,000 --> 00:17:34,000
 And I think it has two elements here.

123
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:41,000
 On the one side, it's the return on household savings that remain very low.

124
00:17:41,000 --> 00:17:50,000
 And the old story of all saving only going to very traditional form of investment with very low returns.

125
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:54,000
 But on the other side, that innovative firms don't have financing.

126
00:17:54,000 --> 00:18:06,000
 And the solution in the region is tricky because many countries are looking at how to deepen their own capital markets.

127
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:10,000
 While the real point is also how to integrate the capital markets.

128
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:17,000
 And how to have flowing resources that come from all over Europe also in the region.

129
00:18:17,000 --> 00:18:22,000
 And I think that's an important element to look at.

130
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:28,000
 So, in fact, I think the new integration results is very strong in the region.

131
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:35,000
 But they may face more the cost of the unfinished work.

132
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:39,000
 We go to a second point.

133
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:46,000
 And it's in the current situation, finishing the work is fundamental.

134
00:18:46,000 --> 00:18:48,000
 It's fundamental at the European level.

135
00:18:48,000 --> 00:18:51,000
 And I think it's very important also for the region.

136
00:18:51,000 --> 00:19:01,000
 It's fundamental because at the end, we end up in a situation in which Europe has an opportunity to become a third pole.

137
00:19:01,000 --> 00:19:08,000
 With U.S. kind of declining rule and China on the other side.

138
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:10,000
 Europe has the opportunity.

139
00:19:10,000 --> 00:19:22,000
 And it's a once in centuries and century opportunity of strengthening the international rule of Europe and of the euro.

140
00:19:22,000 --> 00:19:30,000
 And I think that has to come with more integration also at the European level.

141
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:37,000
 From the discussion we are having, I think there is a risk that if it's not coming through the integration,

142
00:19:37,000 --> 00:19:47,000
 some countries will try to find the sweet spot of having, like the Dubrovnik case that was quoted,

143
00:19:47,000 --> 00:19:53,000
 of finding the Singapore rule of small open economies trying to have advantage.

144
00:19:53,000 --> 00:20:02,000
 But I think the equilibrium of a more integrated Europe is much better for the single countries and for Europe overall.

145
00:20:02,000 --> 00:20:05,000
 Yurushka, so let's follow up on what Deborah said with you.

146
00:20:05,000 --> 00:20:12,000
 So in this case, it means that when it comes to fragmentation affecting the region and Europe's business model,

147
00:20:12,000 --> 00:20:21,000
 is this kind of leads us to some kind of a new growth model concept.

148
00:20:21,000 --> 00:20:24,000
 Yes, I think we can be a little bit bold.

149
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:33,000
 So beyond the wonderful, important measures and avenues that we already have heard in the first panel,

150
00:20:33,000 --> 00:20:41,000
 and now in this panel from my colleagues, I think we can maybe step back and say,

151
00:20:41,000 --> 00:20:46,000
 what are the biggest challenges and risks Europe faces?

152
00:20:46,000 --> 00:20:54,000
 And pair it down to two, which thus far, as far as I can see, have been dealt separately.

153
00:20:54,000 --> 00:21:01,000
 One great challenge, clearly, is the weak military capacity.

154
00:21:01,000 --> 00:21:09,000
 As the commissioner yesterday so brilliantly explained, you know, we are at war.

155
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:11,000
 Europe is at war.

156
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:23,000
 It's being a hot war in Ukraine, but Europe has to, you know, wake up to the fact that the imperial power,

157
00:21:23,000 --> 00:21:27,000
 neighboring Ukraine will not go away.

158
00:21:27,000 --> 00:21:29,000
 Its ambitions will not go away.

159
00:21:29,000 --> 00:21:36,000
 And at the same time, the traditional security umbrella that Europe has accustomed to

160
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:44,000
 and we have enjoyed tremendously as a little bit of a free rider from the U.S. is fading away.

161
00:21:44,000 --> 00:21:46,000
 And that's putting it mildly.

162
00:21:46,000 --> 00:21:58,000
 So we have weak military capacity to defend Europe in a hot war and, in general, to have a defensive position to deter war.

163
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:03,000
 Now, that has been recognized, as the commissioners said, commissioners also said, and several others.

164
00:22:03,000 --> 00:22:07,000
 There is a European rearmament plan and all that.

165
00:22:07,000 --> 00:22:17,000
 Germany, which probably should be at the center of this, has changed its debt rules to allow for more military spending.

166
00:22:17,000 --> 00:22:24,000
 And perhaps, at some point, the ECB will also come into this game, given the this priority.

167
00:22:24,000 --> 00:22:32,000
 But, you know, so this is recognized as a separate issue from all the second threats.

168
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:46,000
 big, grave risk is the stagnation of Europe, the declining productivity, and the relative, growing relative innovation gap toward the U.S.

169
00:22:46,000 --> 00:22:57,000
 There's the druggy report, there's the lottery report, that's, that's, we've heard here, excellent IMF reports, EBRD, EIB reports, World Bank also.

170
00:22:57,000 --> 00:23:01,000
 So, but the two things are kept separately.

171
00:23:01,000 --> 00:23:08,000
 We have to link the military imperative with the economic growth imperative.

172
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:16,000
 And I think it's unavoidable, it's not, it's not a pleasure to say I'm a peace generation, right, and pro-peace.

173
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:30,000
 But we are in a new reality, we have to internalize the new reality, that, that we have to have a high-tech led defense industry, industry, to lead the new economic growth model.

174
00:23:30,000 --> 00:23:33,000
 I think it's inevitable. It's inevitable.

175
00:23:33,000 --> 00:23:43,000
 Link the military imperative with the economic imperative, and have a high-tech, defense industry led economic redevelopment for Europe.

