00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:40,000
 What do they create?

366
00:42:40,000 --> 00:42:41,000
 What do they create?

367
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:42,000
 Do they create jobs?

368
00:42:42,000 --> 00:42:43,000
 Do they create exports?

369
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:44,000
 Do they create innovation?

370
00:42:44,000 --> 00:42:46,000
 Do they support technology adoption?

371
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:50,000
 Why are we supporting, you know, subsistence entrepreneurs?

372
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:52,000
 Why do we support the corner bakery?

373
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:55,000
 Why do we support the corner dry cleaning store?

374
00:42:55,000 --> 00:43:02,000
 I think it's also requires, so a lot of these things at the national level, a lot of these things would require some kind of consensus.

375
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:04,000
 But I think it's absolutely essential.

376
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:08,000
 We need to make our business environment much more dynamic.

377
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:12,000
 Companies have to run faster, given the circumstances around the world.

378
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:23,000
 Deborah, while we are working on those, as Ivaila just mentioned, what do you see as, in this case, the greatest untapped potential within the sea region?

379
00:43:23,000 --> 00:43:38,000
 And how can, you know, this deep integration, including the aspects that Ivaila mentioned, help the region face better the European fragmentation and the global fragmentation at the same time?

380
00:43:38,000 --> 00:43:47,000
 I think, still one of the strongest potential of the region is related to the dynamic industrial base.

381
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:54,000
 And that's actually one of the elements that I think the region really has to continue to cherish.

382
00:43:54,000 --> 00:44:05,000
 Also because with the old global adjustments, actually the region could gain in part of the readjustment waves.

383
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:14,000
 We have seen, so we were trying to look at the shocks of the past years.

384
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:24,000
 So not yet this shock, but the previous one, the pandemic, the old Suez channel, et cetera.

385
00:44:24,000 --> 00:44:28,000
 And now European firms have been adjusting to those shocks.

386
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:34,000
 And I think it's interesting to think also for the future challenge coming.

387
00:44:34,000 --> 00:44:47,000
 So what we've seen is that when firms were affected by the big disruptions of the last years, the first reaction has been a lot of investment in inventories, in digital tracking.

388
00:44:47,000 --> 00:44:56,000
 That is a way for managing better your value chain and know where the problem are happening and how to adjust.

389
00:44:56,000 --> 00:44:59,000
 And then the last point was a lot of diversification.

390
00:44:59,000 --> 00:45:06,000
 So rather than complete retrenching, creating an alternative on your supply.

391
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:13,000
 And on that side, the central eastern Europe was also one of the opportunity on the diversification.

392
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:15,000
 And that was a positive element.

393
00:45:15,000 --> 00:45:33,000
 So in fact, this tells us that even in the new global readjustment, the central eastern Europe can get a little bit more of this intra-EU market diversification effect.

394
00:45:33,000 --> 00:45:38,000
 And that can be positive for the region.

395
00:45:38,000 --> 00:45:48,000
 There is one element that I think is quite important for the region and for the consideration that we'll be taking at the European level overall.

396
00:45:48,000 --> 00:45:51,000
 The region actually has quite strong ties.

397
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:57,000
 As we said, not so strongly affected directly by the U.S., but indirectly.

398
00:45:57,000 --> 00:46:06,000
 But the region has stronger ties also with China, both on the industrial, manufacturing, import side.

399
00:46:06,000 --> 00:46:07,000
 That is important.

400
00:46:07,000 --> 00:46:09,000
 And FDI in the region.

401
00:46:09,000 --> 00:46:14,000
 And also part of innovation related to some of these FDIs.

402
00:46:14,000 --> 00:46:24,000
 So the way in which Europe will define strategic autonomy and the decision that will be taken will be quite important for the region.

403
00:46:24,000 --> 00:46:30,000
 And I think, in fact, diversification is the key word.

404
00:46:30,000 --> 00:46:34,000
 Diversification means you don't go only on one side.

405
00:46:34,000 --> 00:46:38,000
 You protect, you make sure that you have alternatives.

406
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:46,000
 But this is a very important point, I think, for the region to be defined.

407
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:49,000
 There is talking about the potential.

408
00:46:49,000 --> 00:47:01,000
 I think there is another element that we try to keep on top of policy attention that I think is also quite relevant for the region.

409
00:47:01,000 --> 00:47:06,000
 We talk a lot about climate change and the climate policies.

410
00:47:06,000 --> 00:47:13,000
 Now climate seems to be a bad word in the U.S. and some other part of the world.

411
00:47:13,000 --> 00:47:20,000
 But I think for Europe and also for Central Eastern Europe, there are various reasons why it remains central.

412
00:47:20,000 --> 00:47:25,000
 First of all, Europe is an energy importing continent.

413
00:47:25,000 --> 00:47:37,000
 And having a transformed energy sector, which is more diversified, if you want, but also more self-sufficient, is extremely important.

414
00:47:37,000 --> 00:47:53,000
 So the whole transformation of the energy market through renewable, through energy generation, internal energy generation, potentially also nuclear, could be, is something that is in the interest of Europe.

415
00:47:53,000 --> 00:48:03,000
 And it will also be very beneficial for the corporate sector in the medium term when prices then will adjust to the new structure.

416
00:48:03,000 --> 00:48:13,000
 But also, it's not only the energy market side, but it's also the green tech sector that is quite interesting.

417
00:48:13,000 --> 00:48:21,000
 We all talk about the fact that China is excellent, but it's true China is excellent, but Europe is also very good.

418
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:28,000
 Actually, there has been a very strong growth in the market of green tech export product, and Europe is catching it.

419
00:48:28,000 --> 00:48:31,000
 The sea region is really catching it.

420
00:48:31,000 --> 00:48:37,000
 So it's actually a good sector for Europe to continue to invest in.

421
00:48:37,000 --> 00:48:45,000
 And also, in the innovation point of view, true China is very good, but Europe is at the center of innovation networks.

422
00:48:45,000 --> 00:49:00,000
 So, on my side, the potential is also really keeping the net zero policy and strategy really firm at the center also for the region and for Europe, and that will also bring opportunities.

423
00:49:00,000 --> 00:49:04,000
 So if we talk about the potential, I think that's an important one.

424
00:49:04,000 --> 00:49:11,000
 Pireshko, what do you think when it comes to the potential, as Deborah mentioned?

425
00:49:11,000 --> 00:49:13,000
 I very much agree with the potential.

426
00:49:13,000 --> 00:49:25,000
 I think -- maybe I point out another avenue for further potential.

427
00:49:25,000 --> 00:49:47,000
 And that, given that this is a central bank, National Bank of Croatia and IMF conference, maybe it's appropriate to bring in potential monetary policy tools that can also further integration.

428
00:49:47,000 --> 00:49:48,000
 What we are looking at, right?

429
00:49:48,000 --> 00:50:00,000
 And what the region can do and what Europe can do, sort of old Europe, advanced Europe, as you wish, can do for the region.

430
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:17,000
 And let me make the pitch for what is now being discussed in the corridors of central banks in central Europe more vividly, I think, than before.

431
00:50:17,000 --> 00:50:44,000
 after the post COVID inflation fighting period, and given the security situation on the eastern front, is that the benefits of being in the euro, and the euro as an integrating tool, is back on people's minds agenda, if it's not still on the political policy agenda.

432
00:50:44,000 --> 00:51:11,000
 And that is based on new evidence, not on all debates, whether, you know, this region is an optimal currency area with the advanced Europe, or debating whether the euro is an appropriately completed project, given that there is no fiscal authority, central authority, and all the rest of it.

433
00:51:11,000 --> 00:51:36,000
 So the problems with the structure, it's not related to some perceived benefits, imagined benefits of monetary sovereignty, for very small, open economy, next door, to a hopefully, you know, more and more global reserve currency.

434
00:51:36,000 --> 00:51:45,000
 So we have to look at new evidence, not old, you know, dogmas, if I may put it a little bit too harshly.

435
00:51:45,000 --> 00:51:48,000
 New evidence. What's the new evidence?

436
00:51:48,000 --> 00:52:10,000
 The new evidence is that fighting inflation, for in central Europe, where countries were similarly hit, similar structures, similarly hit by the COVID crisis, obviously, but then the Russia imperial war impact, the energy crisis.

437
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:27,000
 So, but have different monetary regimes, some countries are in the euro, have been in the euro, fighting this, and others enjoyed still, you know, outside monetary policy sovereignty.

438
00:52:27,000 --> 00:52:40,000
 So, it's important to compare how the two regimes in this natural experiment, same shock, same structure, but different monetary regimes, how they compare.

439
00:52:40,000 --> 00:53:07,000
 So, we compared with Reina Martin, the National Bank of Slovakia, we compared inflation-fighting performance of Slovakia, which is in the eurozone, obviously, and policies, you know, member of the ECB, and all that, and policies come from the ECB, with that in Poland, the Czech Republics, and Hungary.

440
00:53:07,000 --> 00:53:10,000
 Evidence. What's the evidence? What's the evidence? What's the test?

441
00:53:10,000 --> 00:53:23,000
 And the evidence is very clearly that, A, inflation actually, despite the same shock, same structure, the inflation was the lowest in Slovakia, being in the eurozone.

442
00:53:23,000 --> 00:53:49,000
 Even though the ECB started increasing, and thus Slovakia started to increase interest rates belatedly, arguably, and then that's a strong criticism, I think, ECB, other advanced countries, started later, but they needed, actually, much less of an increase in interest rate to fight similar inflationary pressures,

443
00:53:49,000 --> 00:53:54,000
 than what Hungary, the Poles, and the Czechs had to endure.

444
00:53:54,000 --> 00:54:09,000
 So, the sacrifice ratio, one way or the other, so the output decline required to bring down inflation, 1% of sort of a unit of inflation, was lower in Slovakia.

445
00:54:09,000 --> 00:54:23,000
 This was clearly, despite the delayed implementation in the ECB policies reacting to the inflation pressure relative to monetary sovereignty countries, enjoying monetary sovereignty.

446
00:54:23,000 --> 00:54:28,000
 Inflation was lower, cost of bringing down inflation much lower.

447
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:45,000
 On top of it, you know, Slovakia enjoyed the benefit of being, you know, enjoying the benefit of a massive, more credible, and massive balance sheet central bank, the collective balance sheet of the ECB.

448
00:54:47,000 --> 00:55:01,000
 And they didn't need to beg for currency swaps and repos from the ECB, which all these countries, of course, outside needed, because much of the trade is already in Euro.

449
00:55:02,000 --> 00:55:17,000
 So, overall, this recent experience would suggest to an economist that there were scarcely no benefits for monetary sovereignty fighting inflation,

450
00:55:17,000 --> 00:55:31,000
 And there were only upsides given of membership, given lower inflation, and given much easier crisis management within the Euro zone for a small open economy than outside.

451
00:55:31,000 --> 00:55:44,000
 So, this, sorry for the long story, but I think it's very important to internalize and look at new evidence of Euro integration now.

452
00:55:44,000 --> 00:55:58,000
 And countries to do, I think, everything that is possible to line up, you know, where trade is already, you know, concentrated, where invoicing is in Euro,

453
00:55:58,000 --> 00:56:09,000
 where there is a preference for the Euro, where 50%, up to 50% of deposits and loans are in Euro anyways, even if when you are outside.

454
00:56:11,000 --> 00:56:15,000
 And do everything that is needed to get into Euro.

455
00:56:15,000 --> 00:56:23,000
 The Euro, in the end, has been as much a political tool as an economic tool.

456
00:56:23,000 --> 00:56:29,000
 I know central bankers don't like to hear that, you know, this is a separate thing, monetary, etc.

457
00:56:29,000 --> 00:56:45,000
 No, this has been a political project, so let's complete the political project with the necessary grey rights, with the necessary conditions, maybe a little bit better and look it more, you know, generously at certain cases,

458
00:56:45,000 --> 00:56:57,000
 such as those countries in this region, which unilaterally had to adopt the Euro as part of the EU-sponsored peace ban, Montenegro, Bosnia-Herzegovina, and they're already using the Euro.

459
00:56:57,000 --> 00:57:04,000
 So maybe a little bit more out-of-the-boss thinking in southern Eastern Europe, on top of everything.

460
00:57:04,000 --> 00:57:11,000
 We'll have to wrap up this part, because I'm afraid that we're going into the conclusion part, and I want to hear more about this later.

461
00:57:11,000 --> 00:57:22,000
 Let's conclude this EU-level action part that we are trying to somehow wrap up within a couple of minutes here.

462
00:57:22,000 --> 00:57:38,000
 I want to specifically ask you regarding the recent reinforcement progress, if you could comment on that one, and also the issue of better alignment and use of the EU funds in this regard.

463
00:57:38,000 --> 00:57:39,000
 Thank you.

464
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:41,000
 So let me again start with a higher-level comment.

465
00:57:41,000 --> 00:57:45,000
 So EU legislation can take two main forms.

466
00:57:45,000 --> 00:57:48,000
 One is regulation, and the other is directive.

467
00:57:48,000 --> 00:57:55,000
 When it's a regulation, it sets clearly from the first to the last sentence what countries must do.

468
00:57:55,000 --> 00:58:07,000
 If it's a directive, then it sets the broad guidelines, and countries have to transpose them into their national laws, national legal systems.

469
00:58:07,000 --> 00:58:13,000
 Now, almost all single market issues are directives, not regulations.

470
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:24,000
 So EU countries could decide, okay, instead of directive, we have this regulation, which fully specifies, for example, how architects should operate in the EU.

471
00:58:24,000 --> 00:58:29,000
 And there would be zero barrier for one architect moving from one country to another.

472
00:58:29,000 --> 00:58:31,000
 But EU countries don't want that.

473
00:58:31,000 --> 00:58:41,000
 So they instead opted for directives, and then countries have to obviously incorporate those directives into the national legal systems.

474
00:58:41,000 --> 00:58:43,000
 And this is where the problem comes.

475
00:58:43,000 --> 00:59:00,000
 So I think when we are blaming limited or still frictions and excessive burdensome cross-border provision of services, we primarily have to blame EU members for not going for regulations, but instead directives.

476
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:14,000
 Now, there are lots of tools available for the European Commission, which within this political framework tries to enforce still as much harmonized national implementation as possible.

477
00:59:14,000 --> 00:59:18,000
 So one is, for example, the transposition.

478
00:59:18,000 --> 00:59:33,000
 So the Commission reports a so-called transposition deficit, in which it looks at, you know, how many countries have failed to transpose a certain EU directive, and also whether it's just a recent directive or directive that has been there for long.

479
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:36,000
 So I just looked at the recent scoreboard.

480
00:59:36,000 --> 00:59:40,000
 For example, Croatia is somewhere in the midfield of EU countries.

481
00:59:40,000 --> 00:59:43,000
 Slovenia is in the frontrunner.

482
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:46,000
 Bulgaria is in the lagging countries.

483
00:59:46,000 --> 00:59:50,000
 So not that surprising, given the institutional quality.

484
00:59:50,000 --> 00:59:52,000
 Another is the infringements.

485
00:59:52,000 --> 01:00:02,000
 And another indicator is the so-called conformity deficit, which looks at, after transposition, whether or how much it indeed in line with.

486
01:00:02,000 --> 01:00:09,000
 Is it in line with the principles put forward in the directives?

487
01:00:09,000 --> 01:00:16,000
 And if I look at my own country, Hungary, Hungary is among the best in transposition, but one of the worst in the conformity.

488
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:22,000
 So it seems that Hungarians transpose very quickly and everything, but they don't do it properly.

489
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:25,000
 So there are lots of infringement procedures.

490
01:00:25,000 --> 01:00:32,000
 And the commission, that's a legal procedure that the commission is pushing countries to do that.

491
01:00:32,000 --> 01:00:38,000
 There are also lots of alternative, somewhat softer tools to enforce a single market.

492
01:00:38,000 --> 01:00:47,000
 There is a so-called EU pilot dialogue, which is a kind of informal exchanges between the commission and member states, you know, trying to help them.

493
01:00:47,000 --> 01:00:58,000
 There is a big information system called internal market information system, which connects, you know, across border, local central authorities and everyone.

494
01:00:58,000 --> 01:01:00,000
 There is also a notification system.

495
01:01:00,000 --> 01:01:04,000
 Whenever a country does something related to the single market, they have to submit a notification.

496
01:01:04,000 --> 01:01:17,000
 Again, I just checked the recent commission report from this year in which they reported that in 2024, 755 draft technical regulations were notified to the commission.

497
01:01:17,000 --> 01:01:32,000
 So instead of having, of course, many, for many different products and services, but instead of having, you know, standardized requirements at the EU level, national governments and parliaments decide on their own.

498
01:01:32,000 --> 01:01:34,000
 Then they have to notify the commission.

499
01:01:34,000 --> 01:01:42,000
 And then the commission checks whether, you know, they are in line with the EU and standards and sometimes find it is not and requests changes.

500
01:01:42,000 --> 01:01:54,000
 So, so again, I think that that second to blame, I would rather blame member states for not, not going for, for, for EU, why, why, why, why regulations?

501
01:01:54,000 --> 01:02:05,000
 Now, if you look at what happened in the, in the, in the region, I mean, for example, the transportation deficit went up, you know, during the COVID crisis, it came down a bit.

502
01:02:05,000 --> 01:02:13,000
 The conformity deficit is, is, is going up and down, so there is no, no permanent changes there.

503
01:02:13,000 --> 01:02:22,000
 But, but certainly, hopefully all these tools are, you know, helping countries and, and this super lengthy commission report always conclude that all these are working.

504
01:02:22,000 --> 01:02:28,000
 The countries are improving their regulatory alignment, you know, the labor markets, legal convergence and so on and so on.

505
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:36,000
 Now, on your, on your second question on the, on, on, on, on the EU, EU budget facilities or second part of your, of your, of your question.

506
01:02:36,000 --> 01:02:46,000
 Um, now certainly, um, I mean, the region is certainly the prime beneficiary of, of, of, of various structural funds.

507
01:02:46,000 --> 01:02:50,000
 And I'm looking at the, at the, at the, at the, at the, at the clock.

508
01:02:50,000 --> 01:02:57,000
 So, so what, what, what could be done is, is, is, um, is already to some extent implemented in, in, in cohesion policy.

509
01:02:57,000 --> 01:03:11,000
 But, but also more forcefully in the recovery and resilience facility, this somehow giving a conditionality, uh, for, for, for certain reforms and investments.

510
01:03:11,000 --> 01:03:21,000
 But in, in, in this case we are talking about reforms, uh, to each, uh, EU, I mean, certainly from, uh, requirements and then the, the countries get, get the funding.

511
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:28,000
 I think that, that's a way indeed to, to push countries to, and they try to do this very difficult, uh, reforms.

512
01:03:28,000 --> 01:03:32,000
 Which again, in the region, being a main beneficiary might be, might be, might be an effective tool.

513
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:40,000
 Right. Uh, and you kind of brought us to this third part when we're gonna, I, when I want to ask all the speakers regarding the, uh, political and institutional obstacles.

514
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:41,000
 As well.

515
01:03:41,000 --> 01:03:46,000
 But before I do that, could we please bring back the poll, um, we're gonna reopen it now.

516
01:03:46,000 --> 01:03:47,000
 There's no pressure.

517
01:03:47,000 --> 01:03:49,000
 Well, there's about 10 minutes you have.

518
01:03:49,000 --> 01:03:52,000
 Um, look at it again.

519
01:03:52,000 --> 01:04:05,000
 And we gonna keep it open as I want to go for the final thoughts with the speakers about the, uh, political or institutional obstacles when it comes to preventing deeper integration.

520
01:04:05,000 --> 01:04:14,000
 Uh, Ivala, may I ask you of those when it comes to, um, to the need for more of, uh, political will?

521
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:20,000
 I mean, when countries join the European Union, you give a lot of sovereignty, right?

522
01:04:20,000 --> 01:04:21,000
 Mm-hmm.

523
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:35,000
 And so, therefore, subsequently, trying to streamline regulations, make business easier, you know, stop coddling incumbents, uh, promote, uh, technology adoption, innovation.

524
01:04:35,000 --> 01:04:50,000
 I, I frankly don't see that as much of a loss of sovereignty as, as, as, uh, rather, I mean, how do we make for a much more dynamic both, both countries and, uh, a more dynamic union?

525
01:04:50,000 --> 01:05:04,000
 Obviously, for the small and open economies in our region, especially those that are not members, but even the EU members having a dynamic and vibrant European Union is crucially in our national interest and would certainly enhance, uh, our sovereignty.

526
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:08,000
 So, I, I would not agree with, uh, some of these conclusions here.

527
01:05:08,000 --> 01:05:09,000
 Thank you, Deborah.

528
01:05:09,000 --> 01:05:10,000
 To you.

529
01:05:10,000 --> 01:05:23,000
 I think, uh, I'm, uh, I'm thinking, uh, also at, uh, what can we do as institution, uh, to support, uh, more, uh, actively the, the, the European, uh, approach.

530
01:05:23,000 --> 01:05:32,000
 And I think, uh, I, I come back to, to what we have been discussing a lot, uh, those, uh, Dombrowski was mentioning.

531
01:05:32,000 --> 01:05:50,000
 If, uh, the objective is really this, uh, simplification, integration, uh, and investment, uh, then, uh, institutions like us can do a lot on, uh, the investment side, uh, to try to bring, uh, more resources, uh, also toward, uh, the projects that are more on the European, uh, point of view.

532
01:05:50,000 --> 01:06:05,000
 And, uh, and, uh, and, uh, uh, from the AB side, we are, uh, actually, now we are asking, asking our shareholder to allow us to expand our, uh, activities to 100 billion lending per year.

533
01:06:05,000 --> 01:06:09,000
 And, uh, we have a few elements which I think can make the difference.

534
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:13,000
 And not only us, also institution, other institution can do it.

535
01:06:13,000 --> 01:06:16,000
 But I think it's a quite interesting, uh, to look at.

536
01:06:16,000 --> 01:06:24,000
 First of all, we are in a moment with many diverging priorities in terms of, uh, investment and public investment.

537
01:06:24,000 --> 01:06:37,000
 And I think, uh, there is, uh, a rule of rethinking, uh, how to have, uh, financial instruments that are actually ways in which the public sector, the risk investment for the private sector to intervene.

538
01:06:37,000 --> 01:06:42,000
 In the region, uh, there is still a very little use of these financial instruments.

539
01:06:42,000 --> 01:06:48,000
 And I think it's a very important, uh, to catalyze investment in specific policy area.

540
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:50,000
 This is a one point.

541
01:06:50,000 --> 01:06:58,000
 The second point, uh, as I was saying, as an institution, we continue to have a very, very strong focus on climate.

542
01:06:58,000 --> 01:07:09,000
 And, uh, we are adding, uh, an additional focus, uh, which we already had, but we are expanding it, uh, in terms of innovation finance.

543
01:07:09,000 --> 01:07:18,000
